  "text": "Blood samples were also stored at −80 ∘ C for further assessment of cystatin-C (Cys-C) and SAA. Cys-C is used as an endogenous marker for GFR, more precise than creatinine [CITATION_1] . Serum Cys-C was measured using quantitative enhanced immunonephelometry method (with commercially available assay developed by DADE Behring). The producer recommended the normal range of Cys-C between 0.53 and 0.95 mg/L independently of sex, age, and body mass. Serum concentration of SAA was determined by a commercial enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), with detection limit 0.005 mg/L (Human SAA; BioSource Europe S.A., Belgium). According to literature, SAA normal reference range is under 10 mg/L [CITATION_2] .",
